<section class="bg-green-950 text-white py-16 md:py-24"><div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><p class="text-green-300 font-semibold text-sm uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Water Where It Counts</p><h1 class="font-heading text-5xl md:text-6xl font-bold mb-6">Drip Irrigation in Las Cruces, NM</h1><p class="text-green-100 text-lg max-w-2xl mb-8">Drip delivers water directly to the root zone — no overspray, no evaporation loss, no wet sidewalks. It's the most efficient way to water in the desert, and it's what every xeriscape, tree, and shrub bed in Las Cruces should be on.</p><div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4"><a href="/contact/" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-8 py-3 bg-green-700 text-white font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-green-600 transition-colors">Schedule a Free Consultation</a><a href="tel:575-635-8883" class="inline-flex items-center justify-center px-8 py-3 border-2 border-green-400 text-green-300 font-semibold rounded-lg hover:bg-green-900 transition-colors">Call (575) 635-8883</a></div></div></section>

<section class="py-16 bg-white"><div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center"><div><h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">Why Drip Works Better Here</h2><p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Traditional sprinklers lose a huge percentage of water to evaporation and wind — both of which Las Cruces has plenty of. Drip irrigation puts water right at the base of each plant, below the mulch line, where it soaks into the root zone instead of evaporating into the air.</p><p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">We design drip systems zoned by plant water needs. Desert-adapted plants get less, newly planted trees get more, and everything runs on a schedule that matches the city ordinance. The result: healthier plants, lower water bills, and zero runoff onto the sidewalk.</p></div><div><img src="/assets/images/brainards-drip-irrigation-1d7434e8.jpeg" alt="Drip irrigation system in a Las Cruces landscape" width="305" height="331" loading="lazy" class="rounded-xl shadow-lg w-full"></div></div></section>

<section class="py-16 bg-green-50"><div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8"><div class="text-center mb-12"><h2 class="font-heading text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900">Drip Irrigation FAQ</h2></div><div class="space-y-4">
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Can I convert my sprinklers to drip?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Yes. We convert spray zones to drip all the time — especially when homeowners switch from turf to xeriscape. We cap the spray heads, run drip tubing, and reprogram the controller for the lower flow rates.</div></details>
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">How much water does drip save?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">Drip systems use 30–50% less water than traditional sprinklers for the same planted area. The savings come from eliminating overspray, wind drift, and surface evaporation.</div></details>
<details class="group bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm"><summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer"><span class="font-heading font-medium text-gray-900">Does drip clog easily?</span><svg class="w-5 h-5 text-green-700 transition-transform group-open:rotate-180" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/></svg></summary><div class="px-6 pb-6 text-gray-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">We install inline filters and use pressure-compensating emitters that resist clogging. Las Cruces water is hard, so filters are essential. With proper filtration and occasional flushing, drip systems run reliably for years.</div></details>
</div></div></section>

